{
  "text": "In vivo CTL assay. As previously described [CITATION_1] , splenocytes from nontransgenic B10.D2 mice were isolated and split into 2 groups. Group 1 was left untreated, while group 2 was loaded with synthetic immunodominant HA class I peptide (IYSTVASSL) at a concentration of 10 \u03bcg/ml, then washed 3 times, counted, and resuspended. Group 1 cells were then labeled as CFSE lo and group 2 as CFSE hi by incubation with 0.25 mM or 2.5 mM CFSE, respectively. After labeling, cells were thoroughly washed with HBSS and counted. An equal number of HA-loaded CFSE hi and unloaded CFSE lo target cells were combined and administered by tail-vein injection. Eighteen hours after target cell transfer, splenocytes from recipient mice were analyzed by FACS, and the relative cell numbers in CFSE hi versus CFSE lo peaks were determined to quantify percentage of specific lysis. Representative examples of acquired data are shown in Figure 5A .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "19983364"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "19983364": {
      "title": "Tumor-specific CD4+ T cells have a major \"post-licensing\" role in CTL mediated anti-tumor immunity",
      "abstract": "A number of tumor studies have indicated a link between CD4 help and the magnitude and persistence of CTL activity; however, the mechanisms underlying this have been largely unclear. To evaluate and determine the mechanisms by which CD4+ T cells synergize with CD8+ T cells to prevent tumor growth, we used the novel technique of monitoring in vivo CTL by labeling target cells with CFSE. This approach was supported by the direct visualization of CTL using peptide-MHC tetramers to follow tumor-specific T cells. The data presented demonstrate that while cotransfer of Ag-specific CD4+ T cells was not required for the generation of CTLs, because adoptive transfer of CD8+ T cells alone was sufficient, CD4+ T cells were required for the maintenance of CD8+ T cell numbers. Our data suggest that there is a correlation among the number of CD8+ T cells, in vivo CTL function, and IFN-\u03b3 production, with no evidence of a partial or nonresponsive phenotype among tetramer-positive cells. We also show that CD4+ T cells are required for CD8+ T cell infiltration of the tumor."
    }
  }
}